ly visual simulation where selected neurons carry **surface-wave dynamics** across their morphology, driven by a **synthetic visual scene generator**, and presented through a strong **interactive UI / analysis layer**.\\ndocs/milestones.md:88:| 2 | Lock the circuit boundary | Shared leaning programming (65/35) | Jack lead, Grant supports | Active visual subset and context graph |\\ndocs/milestones.md:92:| 6 | Construct surface discretizations and operators | Math/physics-heavy (30/70) | Grant lead, Jack implements | Laplacians, patch graphs, transfer operators |\\ndocs/milestones.md:96:| 10 | Implement the surface-wave engine | Math/physics-heavy (25/75) | Grant lead, Jack implements | Running wave dynamics on neuron surfaces |\\ndocs/milestones.md:101:| 15 | Build experiment orchestration and ablations | Programming-heavy (80/20) | Jack lead | Batch runs, manifests, comparisons |\\ndocs/milestones.md:103:| 17 | Extend to whole-brain context views | Programming-heavy (75/25) | Jack lead | Context graph around the active visual circuit |\\ndocs/milestones.md:119:**Morphology-resolved surface dynamics constitute an additional intraneuronal computational degree of freedom, capable of shaping circuit input-output transformations through distributed spatiotemporal state on neuronal structure.**\\ndocs/milestones.md:123:**In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.**\\ndocs/milestones.md:130:* surface-localized inputs on explicit T4/T5 morphology regions  \\ndocs/milestones.md:131:* surface propagation over a morphology graph  \\ndocs/milestones.md:141:* hand-fitted per-synapse delays granted only to the surface model\\ndocs/milestones.md:151: In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\\ndocs/milestones.md:156:**What observable will convince you that the surface model matters?**  \\ndocs/milestones.md:171:* **Weak:** the surface model shows propagation or spread that the point model cannot show by construction  \\ndocs/milestones.md:172:* **Moderate:** the surface model changes a shared readout such as null-direction suppression, latency, or DSI  \\ndocs/milestones.md:178:1. **`0–10 s`**: show a simple moving edge across a small retinotopic patch  \\ndocs/milestones.md:179:2. **`10–25 s`**: split screen with matched point baseline on the left and surface model on the right for the same T4/T5-centered circuit  \\ndocs/milestones.md:187:* split view showing baseline scalar activity versus surface-state activity on morphology  \\ndocs/milestones.md:208:* creating the experiment manifest schema  \\ndocs/milestones.md:262:Milestone 2 is locked to a **central-equatorial local motion patch built around one horizontal ON/OFF channel**.\\ndocs/milestones.md:264:The default active graph should use the **balanced local-motion subnetwork**:\\ndocs/milestones.md:266:* **surface-simulated:** T4a and T5a  \\ndocs/milestones.md:275:**Context graph**  \\ndocs/milestones.md:278:**Candidate graph**  \\ndocs/milestones.md:279: The locked active graph, abstracted upstream drive nodes, context-only direct partners, and downstream promotion candidates for later milestones.\\ndocs/milestones.md:281:**Active graph**  \\ndocs/milestones.md:282: A single central-equatorial contiguous patch containing:\\ndocs/milestones.md:284:* T4a and T5a in surface mode  \\ndocs/milestones.md:312:**T4a/T5a \\\\+ direct ON/OFF reduced inputs \\\\+ central patch \\\\+ terminal readout**\\ndocs/milestones.md:323:* expand the **retinotopic patch** only when the target shifts from local motion computation to optic-flow or larger-field behavior  \\ndocs/milestones.md:3