S_READY if bundle_paths.raw_mesh_path.exists() else ASSET_STATUS_MISSING,\\nsrc/flywire_wave/mesh_pipeline.py:723:    if bundle_paths.raw_skeleton_path.exists():\\nsrc/flywire_wave/mesh_pipeline.py:734:            \\\"surface_graph_edge_count\\\": int(descriptor_payload[\\\"surface_graph_edge_count\\\"]),\\nsrc/flywire_wave/mesh_pipeline.py:735:            \\\"patch_count\\\": int(descriptor_payload[\\\"patch_count\\\"]),\\nsrc/flywire_wave/mesh_pipeline.py:736:            \\\"patch_graph_vertex_count\\\": int(descriptor_payload[\\\"patch_graph_vertex_count\\\"]),\\nsrc/flywire_wave/mesh_pipeline.py:737:            \\\"patch_graph_edge_count\\\": int(descriptor_payload[\\\"patch_graph_edge_count\\\"]),\\nsrc/flywire_wave/mesh_pipeline.py:738:            \\\"surface_to_patch_count\\\": int(descriptor_payload[\\\"surface_to_patch_count\\\"]),\\nsrc/flywire_wave/mesh_pipeline.py:739:            \\\"patch_generation_method\\\": \\\"deterministic_bfs_partition\\\",\\nsrc/flywire_wave/mesh_pipeline.py:741:            \\\"raw_mesh_face_count\\\": original_face_count,\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T170513Z/FW-M5-005_Ship_offline_geometry_preview_tooling_for_raw_simplified_skeleton_and_patchified_assets/stdout.jsonl:29:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_14\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '240,460p' README.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\\nThe Milestone 4 selector is now preset-driven. The sample config defines three\\nnamed presets:\\n\\n- `motion_minimal`\\n- `motion_medium`\\n- `motion_dense`\\n\\nEach run writes a root-id list, selected-neuron CSV, stats JSON, manifest JSON,\\nand a lightweight Markdown/Mermaid preview under `data/interim/subsets/<preset>/`.\\nThe active preset also refreshes `paths.selected_root_ids` so downstream mesh and\\nasset steps can switch inputs by config alone.\\n\\n```bash\\npython scripts/01_select_subset.py --config config/local.yaml\\n```\\n\\nSelect a specific preset:\\n\\n```bash\\npython scripts/01_select_subset.py --config config/local.yaml --preset motion_dense\\n```\\n\\nGenerate every preset declared in the config:\\n\\n```bash\\npython scripts/01_select_subset.py --config config/local.yaml --all-presets\\n```\\n\\nThis writes the active root-id list to something like:\\n\\n```text\\ndata/interim/root_ids_visual_sample.txt\\n```\\n\\nAnd writes per-preset reports to:\\n\\n```text\\ndata/interim/subsets/\\n```\\n\\n### 8) Fetch meshes + skeletons\\n\\n```bash\\npython scripts/02_fetch_meshes.py --config config/local.yaml\\n```\\n\\nThis downloads raw per-neuron assets into:\\n\\n```text\\ndata/interim/meshes_raw/\\ndata/interim/skeletons_raw/\\n```\\n\\n### 9) Build wave-ready mesh assets\\n\\n```bash\\npython scripts/03_build_wave_assets.py --config config/local.yaml\\n```\\n\\nThis creates:\\n- simplified meshes,\\n- sparse adjacency,\\n- graph Laplacians,\\n- an example active patch per neuron.\\n\\nOutputs land in:\\n\\n```text\\ndata/processed/\\n```\\n\\n## What “meshing for the simulation” means here\\n\\nFor each selected root ID, this scaffold does:\\n\\n1. fetch full-resolution FlyWire mesh,\\n2. simplify it to a target face budget,\\n3. build a sparse surface graph from triangle connectivity,\\n4. compute a graph Laplacian,\\n5. choose an example local patch that can become the wave solver’s active region,\\n6. save everything as `.npz` / `.json` / `.ply`.\\n\\nThat is enough to support:\\n- mesh-resolved wave experiments,\\n- branch/patch-local dynamics,\\n- synapse-to-patch mapping later,\\n- selective promotion of only the currently active neurons.\\n\\n## Milestone 1 design-lock artifacts\\n\\nMilestone 1 is treated here as a design/specification milestone rather than a proof-of-effect milestone.\\n\\n- Roadmap and detailed milestone planning: [`docs/milestones.md`](docs/milestones.md)\\n- Machine-readable design lock and success criteria: [`config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml`](config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml)\\n- Example demo manifest: [`manifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml`](manifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml)\\n- Manifest schema: [`schemas/milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json`](schemas/milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json)\\n\\nValidate the example manifest with:\\n\\n```bash\\nmake validate-manifest\\n```\\n\\nor:\\n\\n```bash\\npython3 scripts/04_validate_manifest.py \\\\\\n  --manifest manifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml \\\\\\n  --schema schemas/milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json \\\\\\n  --design-lock config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml\\n```\\n\\n## Suggested first run for your project\\n\\nDo **not** start by meshing hundreds or thousands of neurons.\\n\\nA good first pass is:\\n- 10–25 visual neurons,\\n- simplify each to ~10k–20k faces,\\n- use one active patch per neuron,\\n- test your wave solver on the patch graph before scaling up.\\n\\nOnce that is stable, you can add:\\n- synaptic placement from CAVE metadata,\\n- cross-neuron coupling,\\n- neuropil-level sheets,\\n- scheduler-driven promotion/demotion.\\n\\n## Make targets\\n\\nThe `Makefile` defaults to `.venv/bin/python` when that virtualenv exists, which makes the local test and pipeline loop work without manually swapping interpreters.\\n\\n```bash\\nmake help\\nmake bootstrap\\nmake test\\nmake smoke\\nmake verify CONFIG=config/local.yaml\\nmake registry CONFIG=config/local.yaml\\nmake select CONFIG=config/local.yaml\\nmake meshes CONFIG=config/local.yaml\\nmake assets CONFIG=config/local.yaml\\nmake validate-manifest\\nmake all CONFIG=config/local.yaml\\n```\\n\\n## Caveats\\n\\n- The full EM/segmentation volumes are massive; this repo intentionally avoids trying to mirror them locally.\\n- FlyWire Codex portal exports can change names over time; check the portal if a filename differs.\\n- Mesh fetching depends on a valid token and network access.\\n- The provided Laplacian is a **starter graph Laplacian**, not a full finite-element surface operator.\\n- This scaffold is for preprocessing / asset generation, not the final simulator.\\n\\n## Good next steps after this scaffold\\n\\n- add synapse-to-vertex projection,\\n- create branch-aware active patches,\\n- build a local wave PDE / reaction-diffusion solver on the simplified mesh graph,\\n- add a scheduler that promotes neurons from latent → mesh-wave only when needed.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T170513Z/FW-M5-005_Ship_offline_geometry_preview_tooling_for_raw_simplified_skeleton_and_patchified_assets/stdout.jsonl:32:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_15\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' docs/pipeline_notes.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Pipeline notes\\n\\n## Recommended workflow\\n\\n1. Use FlyWire Codex bulk exports for stable metadata snapshots.\\n2. Use CAVE / fafbseg for programmatic per-neuron access.\\n3. Build local preprocessed assets so the simulator does not talk to FlyWire live during runtime.\\n\\n## Why this repo uses selective meshing\\n\\nThe female whole brain is the structural scaffold, but the final simulation should only keep a small subset in a mesh-wave state at once. That matches a multiresolution strategy:\\n\\n- whole brain mapped,\\n- selected circuit meshed,\\n- only active patches numerically updated.\\n\\n## Artifact contracts\\n\\n### Subset-selection contract\\n\\nMilestone 4 subset generation writes one artifact bundle per named preset under\\n`data/interim/subsets/<preset>/`:\\n\\n- `root_ids.txt`: simulator-facing root-id list\\n- `selected_neurons.csv`: filtered registry rows for the preset\\n- `subset_stats.json`: graph counts, role counts, and boundary summaries\\n- `subset_manifest.json`: resolved selection rules plus the selected neuron roster\\n- `preview.md`: lightweight Markdown/Mermaid preview for quick inspection\\n\\nThe active preset also refreshes the path named by `config.paths.selected_root_ids`\\nso downstream pipeline steps can switch subsets without code changes.\\n\\n### Geometry handoff contract\\n\\nMilestone 5 uses the versioned geometry bundle contract\\n`geometry_bundle.v1`. One canonical library path builder owns the\\nfilenames below, and both `scripts/02_fetch_meshes.py` plus\\n`scripts/03_build_wave_assets.py` use it directly.\\n\\nPer neuron, the bundle layout is:\\n\\n- `config.paths.meshes_raw_dir/<root_id>.ply`: raw mesh\\n- `config.paths.skeletons_raw_dir/<root_id>.swc`: raw skeleton\\n- `config.paths.processed_mesh_dir/<root_id>.ply`: simplified mesh\\n- `config.paths.processed_graph_dir/<root_id>_graph.npz`: surface graph\\n- `config.paths.processed_graph_dir/<root_id>_patch_graph.npz`: patch graph\\n- `config.paths.processed_graph_dir/<root_id>_descriptors.json`: derived descriptor sidecar\\n- `config.paths.processed_graph_dir/<root_id>_qa.json`: QA sidecar\\n\\nThe processed graph archives intentionally separate fine and coarse data:\\n\\n- the surface graph stores the simplified mesh vertices/faces, sparse surface adjacency/Laplacian arrays, and `surface_to_patch` so every surface vertex has an explicit coarse patch assignment\\n- the patch graph stores sparse coarse adjacency/Laplacian arrays plus `patch_sizes`, `patch_centroids`, `patch_seed_vertices`, and CSR-style `member_vertex_indices` / `member_vertex_indptr` arrays for reconstructing patch membership deterministically\\n\\n`config.paths.manifest_json` records the bundle contract version, dataset,\\nmaterialization version, meshing-config snapshot, and per-root asset\\nstatuses/paths. Raw fetch runs also record `raw_asset_provenance` per\\nroot ID so cache hits, refetches, skips, validation failures, and\\noptional skeleton fetch errors can be audited without reading console\\nlogs. Processed bundle records also expose `artifact_sources` so each\\nsimplified mesh, surface graph, patch graph, and sidecar points back to\\nthe raw mesh and skeleton inputs it was built against.\\n\\nDescriptor and QA rationale:\\n\\n- `docs/geometry_descriptor_qa.md` documents the default `meshing.qa_thresholds`\\n  profile, what each descriptor bucket is meant to capture, and which failed\\n  checks should block downstream use by default.\\n\\nCompatibility shim:\\n\\n- `config.paths.processed_graph_dir/<root_id>_meta.json` is still written as\\n  a legacy metadata pointer so older consumers can keep reading the prior\\n  sidecar name during migration.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T170513Z/FW-M5-005_Ship_offline_geometry_preview_tooling_for_raw_simplified_skeleton_and_patchified_assets/stdout.jsonl:104:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_60\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/bash -lc \\\"nl -ba README.md | sed -n '60,380p'\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"    60\\tflywire_wave_repo/\\n    61\\t├── README.md\\n    62\\t├── AGENTS.md\\n    63\\t├── requirements.txt\\n    64\\t├── pyproject.toml\\n    65\\t├── Makefile\\n    66\\t├── .env.example\\n    67\\t├── config/\\n    68\\t│   ├── milestone_1_design_lock.yaml\\n    69\\t│   └── visual_subset.example.yaml\\n    70\\t├── docs/\\n    71\\t│   ├── geometry_preview.md\\n    72\\t│   ├── milestones.md\\n    73\\t│   ├── pipeline_notes.md\\n    74\\t│   └── subset_presets.md\\n    75\\t├── manifests/\\n    76\\t│   └── examples/\\n    77\\t│       └── milestone_1_demo.yaml\\n    78\\t├── schemas/\\n    79\\t│   └── milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json\\n    80\\t├── scripts/\\n    81\\t│   ├── 00_verify_access.py\\n    82\\t│   ├── build_registry.py\\n    83\\t│   ├── 01_select_subset.py\\n    84\\t│   ├── 02_fetch_meshes.py\\n    85\\t│   ├── 03_build_wave_assets.py\\n    86\\t│   ├── 04_validate_manifest.py\\n    87\\t│   ├── 05_preview_geometry.py\\n    88\\t│   └── setup_flywire_token.py\\n    89\\t├── src/\\n    90\\t│   └── flywire_wave/\\n    91\\t│       ├── __init__.py\\n    92\\t│       ├── config.py\\n    93\\t│       ├── io_utils.py\\n    94\\t│       ├── manifests.py\\n    95\\t│       ├── mesh_pipeline.py\\n    96\\t│       ├── registry.py\\n    97\\t│       └── selection.py\\n    98\\t├── tests/\\n    99\\t│   ├── test_manifest_validation.py\\n   100\\t│   └── test_registry.py\\n   101\\t├── flywire_codex/\\n   102\\t└── data/\\n   103\\t    ├── raw/\\n   104\\t    │   └── codex/\\n   105\\t    ├── interim/\\n   106\\t    └── processed/\\n   107\\t```\\n   108\\t\\n   109\\t## FlyWire Authentication\\n   110\\t\\n   111\\tThis repo uses two separate auth contexts:\\n   112\\t\\n   113\\t- **FlyWire Codex** (`codex.flywire.ai`) for browser/UI access and bulk CSV/static downloads\\n   114\\t- **CAVE / FlyWire API** for local programmatic access through `caveclient`, `fafbseg`, and the repo scripts that read `FLYWIRE_TOKEN` from `.env`\\n   115\\t\\n   116\\tBeing signed into **FlyWire Codex** in the browser does **not** automatically configure local Python access. The `FLYWIRE_TOKEN` value in `.env` should be your **FlyWire/CAVE API token**.\\n   117\\t\\n   118\\tRecommended setup flow:\\n   119\\t\\n   120\\t1. Copy the example env file:\\n   121\\t\\n   122\\t```bash\\n   123\\tcp .env.example .env\\n   124\\t```\\n   125\\t\\n   126\\t2. Launch the helper script:\\n   127\\t\\n   128\\t```bash\\n   129\\tpython scripts/setup_flywire_token.py\\n   130\\t```\\n   131\\t\\n   132\\tThis opens the existing-token page first. If you specifically need to mint a new token, run:\\n   133\\t\\n   134\\t```bash\\n   135\\tpython scripts/setup_flywire_token.py --new-token\\n   136\\t```\\n   137\\t\\n   138\\tCreating a new token may invalidate the previous one.\\n   139\\t\\n   140\\t3. Copy the token from the browser page.\\n   141\\t4. Paste it into `.env` as `FLYWIRE_TOKEN=...`, or rerun the helper with `--write-env` to update `.env` interactively.\\n   142\\t5. Optional: after installing dependencies, save the same token to local CAVE secret storage with `caveclient` if you want machine-wide auth for `caveclient` / `fafbseg`.\\n   143\\t6. Rerun access verification:\\n   144\\t\\n   145\\t```bash\\n   146\\tpython scripts/00_verify_access.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   147\\t```\\n   148\\t\\n   149\\tIf FlyWire's materialization service is temporarily down, the verifier will now\\n   150\\treport that as an upstream outage while still confirming whether your token works\\n   151\\tagainst the global info service. Add `--require-materialize` if you want that\\n   152\\tcase to return a non-zero exit code.\\n   153\\t\\n   154\\tThis keeps the auth split explicit: **FlyWire Codex** handles website browsing/downloads, while `FLYWIRE_TOKEN` handles local API access.\\n   155\\t\\n   156\\t## Quick start\\n   157\\t\\n   158\\t### 1) Create environment\\n   159\\t\\n   160\\t```bash\\n   161\\tgit submodule update --init --recursive\\n   162\\tmake bootstrap\\n   163\\t```\\n   164\\t\\n   165\\tInitialize the pinned `flywire_codex/` submodule once after cloning, then run `make bootstrap` to create `.venv/` if needed, upgrade `pip`, and install the repo in editable mode via [`pyproject.toml`](pyproject.toml).\\n   166\\t\\n   167\\tManual equivalent:\\n   168\\t\\n   169\\t```bash\\n   170\\tpython -m venv .venv\\n   171\\tsource .venv/bin/activate\\n   172\\tpython -m pip install --upgrade pip\\n   173\\tpython -m pip install -e .\\n   174\\t```\\n   175\\t\\n   176\\t### 2) Set up FlyWire authentication\\n   177\\t\\n   178\\t```bash\\n   179\\tcp .env.example .env\\n   180\\tpython scripts/setup_flywire_token.py\\n   181\\t```\\n   182\\t\\n   183\\tThen copy the token from the browser page into `.env` as `FLYWIRE_TOKEN=...`, or rerun the helper with `--write-env` to update `.env` interactively.\\n   184\\t\\n   185\\t### 3) Download the FlyWire Codex metadata exports\\n   186\\t\\n   187\\tPlace the files you downloaded from FlyWire Codex into:\\n   188\\t\\n   189\\t```text\\n   190\\tdata/raw/codex/\\n   191\\t```\\n   192\\t\\n   193\\tRecommended registry inputs:\\n   194\\t\\n   195\\t```text\\n   196\\tdata/raw/codex/classification.csv\\n   197\\tdata/raw/codex/cell_types.csv\\n   198\\tdata/raw/codex/connections_filtered.csv\\n   199\\tdata/raw/codex/neurotransmitter_type_predictions.csv\\n   200\\t```\\n   201\\t\\n   202\\t### 4) Copy the example config\\n   203\\t\\n   204\\t```bash\\n   205\\tcp config/visual_subset.example.yaml config/local.yaml\\n   206\\t```\\n   207\\t\\n   208\\tAll entries under `config.paths` resolve from the repository root, not from\\n   209\\tthe caller's current working directory. You can run the pipeline from another\\n   210\\tdirectory as long as `--config` points to the right file, for example:\\n   211\\t\\n   212\\t```bash\\n   213\\tpython /abs/path/to/flywire_wave_repo/scripts/build_registry.py \\\\\\n   214\\t  --config /abs/path/to/flywire_wave_repo/config/local.yaml\\n   215\\t```\\n   216\\t\\n   217\\t### 5) Verify access\\n   218\\t\\n   219\\t```bash\\n   220\\tpython scripts/00_verify_access.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   221\\t```\\n   222\\t\\n   223\\t### 6) Build the canonical registry\\n   224\\t\\n   225\\tThis normalizes the local Codex exports into one neuron registry, one\\n   226\\tconnectivity registry, and a provenance JSON with pinned snapshot/materialization\\n   227\\tmetadata plus input file fingerprints.\\n   228\\t\\n   229\\t```bash\\n   230\\tpython scripts/build_registry.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   231\\t```\\n   232\\t\\n   233\\tThis writes:\\n   234\\t\\n   235\\t```text\\n   236\\tdata/interim/registry/neuron_registry.csv\\n   237\\tdata/interim/registry/connectivity_registry.csv\\n   238\\tdata/interim/registry/registry_provenance.json\\n   239\\t```\\n   240\\t\\n   241\\t### 7) Select a subset to mesh\\n   242\\t\\n   243\\tThe Milestone 4 selector is now preset-driven. The sample config defines three\\n   244\\tnamed presets:\\n   245\\t\\n   246\\t- `motion_minimal`\\n   247\\t- `motion_medium`\\n   248\\t- `motion_dense`\\n   249\\t\\n   250\\tEach run writes a root-id list, selected-neuron CSV, stats JSON, manifest JSON,\\n   251\\tand a lightweight Markdown/Mermaid preview under `data/interim/subsets/<preset>/`.\\n   252\\tThe active preset also refreshes `paths.selected_root_ids` so downstream mesh and\\n   253\\tasset steps can switch inputs by config alone.\\n   254\\t\\n   255\\t```bash\\n   256\\tpython scripts/01_select_subset.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   257\\t```\\n   258\\t\\n   259\\tSelect a specific preset:\\n   260\\t\\n   261\\t```bash\\n   262\\tpython scripts/01_select_subset.py --config config/local.yaml --preset motion_dense\\n   263\\t```\\n   264\\t\\n   265\\tGenerate every preset declared in the config:\\n   266\\t\\n   267\\t```bash\\n   268\\tpython scripts/01_select_subset.py --config config/local.yaml --all-presets\\n   269\\t```\\n   270\\t\\n   271\\tThis writes the active root-id list to something like:\\n   272\\t\\n   273\\t```text\\n   274\\tdata/interim/root_ids_visual_sample.txt\\n   275\\t```\\n   276\\t\\n   277\\tAnd writes per-preset reports to:\\n   278\\t\\n   279\\t```text\\n   280\\tdata/interim/subsets/\\n   281\\t```\\n   282\\t\\n   283\\t### 8) Fetch meshes + skeletons\\n   284\\t\\n   285\\t```bash\\n   286\\tpython scripts/02_fetch_meshes.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   287\\t```\\n   288\\t\\n   289\\tThis downloads raw per-neuron assets into:\\n   290\\t\\n   291\\t```text\\n   292\\tdata/interim/meshes_raw/\\n   293\\tdata/interim/skeletons_raw/\\n   294\\t```\\n   295\\t\\n   296\\t### 9) Build wave-ready mesh assets\\n   297\\t\\n   298\\t```bash\\n   299\\tpython scripts/03_build_wave_assets.py --config config/local.yaml\\n   300\\t```\\n   301\\t\\n   302\\tThis creates:\\n   303\\t- simplified meshes,\\n   304\\t- sparse adjacency,\\n   305\\t- graph Laplacians,\\n   306\\t- an example active patch per neuron.\\n   307\\t\\n   308\\tOutputs land in:\\n   309\\t\\n   310\\t```text\\n   311\\tdata/processed/\\n   312\\t```\\n   313\\t\\n   314\\t### 10) Generate an offline geometry preview report\\n   315\\t\\n   316\\t```bash\\n   317\\tpython scripts/05_preview_geometry.py --config config/local.yaml --root-id 720575940000000001\\n   318\\t```\\n   319\\t\\n   320\\tIf you omit `--root-id`, the preview script reads `paths.selected_root_ids`.\\n   321\\tReports write to a deterministic directory under:\\n   322\\t\\n   323\\t```text\\n   324\\tdata/processed/previews/\\n   325\\t```\\n   326\\t\\n   327\\tEach preview directory contains a static `index.html`, `summary.json`, and the\\n   328\\texact `root_ids.txt` used for that report. See [`docs/geometry_preview.md`](docs/geometry_preview.md)\\n   329\\tfor the reviewer checklist and a few common invocation patterns.\\n   330\\t\\n   331\\t## What “meshing for the simulation” means here\\n   332\\t\\n   333\\tFor each selected root ID, this scaffold does:\\n   334\\t\\n   335\\t1. fetch full-resolution FlyWire mesh,\\n   336\\t2. simplify it to a target face budget,\\n   337\\t3. build a sparse surface graph from triangle connectivity,\\n   338\\t4. compute a graph Laplacian,\\n   339\\t5. choose an example local patch that can become the wave solver’s active region,\\n   340\\t6. save everything as `.npz` / `.json` / `.ply`.\\n   341\\t\\n   342\\tThat is enough to support:\\n   343\\t- mesh-resolved wave experiments,\\n   344\\t- branch/patch-local dynamics,\\n   345\\t- synapse-to-patch mapping later,\\n   346\\t- selective promotion of only the currently active neurons.\\n   347\\t\\n   348\\t## Milestone 1 design-lock artifacts\\n   349\\t\\n   350\\tMilestone 1 is treated here as a design/specification milestone rather than a proof-of-effect milestone.\\n   351\\t\\n   352\\t- Roadmap and detailed milestone planning: [`docs/milestones.md`](docs/milestones.md)\\n   353\\t- Machine-readable design lock and success criteria: [`config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml`](config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml)\\n   354\\t- Example demo manifest: [`manifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml`](manifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml)\\n   355\\t- Manifest schema: [`schemas/milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json`](schemas/milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json)\\n   356\\t\\n   357\\tValidate the example manifest with:\\n   358\\t\\n   359\\t```bash\\n   360\\tmake validate-manifest\\n   361\\t```\\n   362\\t\\n   363\\tor:\\n   364\\t\\n   365\\t```bash\\n   366\\tpython3 scripts/04_validate_manifest.py \\\\\\n   367\\t  --manifest manifests/examples/milestone_1_demo.yaml \\\\\\n   368\\t  --schema schemas/milestone_1_experiment_manifest.schema.json \\\\\\n   369\\t  --design-lock config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml\\n   370\\t```\\n   371\\t\\n   372\\t## Suggested first run for your project\\n   373\\t\\n   374\\tDo **not** start by meshing hundreds or thousands of neurons.\\n   375\\t\\n   376\\tA good first pass is:\\n   377\\t- 10–25 visual neurons,\\n   378\\t- simplify each to ~10k–20k faces,\\n   379\\t- use one active patch per neuron,\\n   380\\t- test your wave solver on the patch graph before scaling up.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T170513Z/FW-M5-005_Ship_offline_geometry_preview_tooling_for_raw_simplified_skeleton_and_patchified_assets/prompt.md:13:Add offline preview tooling that consumes already-built local geometry bundles and generates an inspection-friendly report for one or more root IDs. The tool can be a script, notebook, or small library-backed report generator, but it should standardize how the team compares raw mesh, simplified mesh, skeleton, surface graph, and patch graph views without requiring live FlyWire access.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/last_message.md:2:- Added a library-owned Milestone 7 contract module in [src/flywire_wave/coupling_contract.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/src/flywire_wave/coupling_contract.py#L10) that centralizes canonical paths for the local synapse registry, per-root incoming/outgoing anchor maps, root coupling indexes, and edge coupling bundles, plus deterministic manifest/discovery helpers.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/last_message.md:3:- Extended the processed manifest writer in [src/flywire_wave/geometry_contract.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/src/flywire_wave/geometry_contract.py#L648) so manifests now emit `_coupling_contract_version`, `_coupling_contract`, and per-root `coupling_bundle` metadata alongside the existing geometry/operator records. `processed_coupling_dir` was added to config defaults/examples in [src/flywire_wave/config.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/src/flywire_wave/config.py), [config/visual_subset.example.yaml](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/config/visual_subset.example.yaml), and [config/milestone_6_verification.yaml](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/config/milestone_6_verification.yaml).\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/last_message.md:4:- Added the decisive design note in [docs/coupling_bundle_design.md](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/docs/coupling_bundle_design.md#L1) and updated [docs/pipeline_notes.md](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/docs/pipeline_notes.md#L86). The default is `distributed_patch_cloud`, with fallback `surface_patch_cloud -> skeleton_segment_cloud -> point_neuron_lumped`, explicit sign/delay rules, and aggregation that preserves sign and delay bins.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/last_message.md:5:- Added regression coverage in [tests/test_coupling_contract.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/tests/test_coupling_contract.py#L46), plus manifest/integration assertions in [tests/test_geometry_contract.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/tests/test_geometry_contract.py#L80) and [tests/test_config_paths.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/tests/test_config_paths.py#L105). Existing operator discovery continues to work unchanged.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/last_message.md:8:- `python3 -m unittest tests.test_coupling_contract -v`\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/last_message.md:1:Implemented FW-M7-005 end-to-end.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/last_message.md:3:- Added the offline report generator in [coupling_inspection.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/src/flywire_wave/coupling_inspection.py:339). It consumes the local synapse registry, edge bundle, root anchor maps, and local geometry assets; writes deterministic `edges-<sorted-edge-slug>/` report bundles; emits `index.html`, `report.md`, `summary.json`, `edges.txt`, per-edge detail JSON, and source/target SVG panels; and computes compact pass/warn/fail QA flags for mapping coverage, artifact consistency, cloud normalization, weight conservation, and delay integrity.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/last_message.md:4:- Added the CLI entrypoint in [08_coupling_inspection.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/scripts/08_coupling_inspection.py:21), the default output path in [config.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/src/flywire_wave/config.py:23), and a `make coupling-inspect` target in [Makefile](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/Makefile:53).\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/last_message.md:5:- Documented the workflow and reviewer guidance in [coupling_inspection.md](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/docs/coupling_inspection.md:1), linked it from [README.md](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/README.md:358), and added the contract note in [pipeline_notes.md](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/docs/pipeline_notes.md:178).\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/last_message.md:6:- Added the fixture smoke test in [test_coupling_inspection.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/tests/test_coupling_inspection.py:24), which builds local fixture assets, runs the script, and asserts deterministic paths plus expected summary/detail fields.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/last_message.md:9:- `.venv/bin/python -m unittest tests.test_coupling_inspection -v`\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/prompt.md:1:Work ticket FW-M7-005: Ship offline coupling inspection and QA tooling so any connectome edge can be visualized and audited.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/prompt.md:4:Source: Milestone 7 roadmap 2026-03-21\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/prompt.md:10:Milestone 7 is only complete if any edge can be inspected and visualized, but the repo currently has no standard workflow for reviewing mapped synapses or inter-neuron transfers offline. A developer could manually open registries and bundle archives, yet there is no repeatable report that shows where an edge reads from the presynaptic neuron, where it lands on the postsynaptic state space, how many synapses were aggregated, what delays or signs were assigned, or whether mapping quality is trustworthy enough for later simulator work.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/prompt.md:13:Add an offline coupling inspection and QA workflow that consumes local synapse registries, anchor maps, geometry or operator bundles, and coupling artifacts to produce review-friendly reports. The workflow should support inspecting a single edge or a small selected set of edges, render the presynaptic readout and postsynaptic landing geometry in a deterministic output directory, summarize aggregation and delay statistics, and emit compact pass, warn, or fail checks for mapping coverage and coupling integrity. The goal is not to build the full UI; it is to make the Milestone 7 handoff inspectable and regression-testable before simulator work begins.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/prompt.md:16:- A documented local command or script can generate a coupling inspection report for one edge or a small edge set using only local cached artifacts and no FlyWire access.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/prompt.md:17:- The report includes at least an edge summary, mapped-synapse or aggregate-landing visualization, presynaptic readout summary, aggregation statistics, delay or sign summary, and coupling QA flags.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/prompt.md:20:- Docs explain how the report should be used to review Milestone 7 outputs and what a reviewer should look for when mapping coverage or coupling quality fails.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/prompt.md:24:- A smoke-style fixture run that generates a coupling inspection report and asserts the summary fields plus deterministic output paths\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-005_Ship_offline_coupling_inspection_and_QA_tooling_so_any_connectome_edge_can_be_visualized_and_audited/prompt.md:27:Assume the earlier Milestone 7 tickets have already landed. Favor lightweight offline artifacts such as Markdown plus images, HTML, or another review-friendly format that does not require interactive infrastructure to be useful.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/prompt.md:1:Work ticket FW-M7-001: Freeze a versioned synapse asset contract and inter-neuron coupling design note.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/prompt.md:4:Source: Milestone 7 roadmap 2026-03-21\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/prompt.md:10:The repo currently stops at per-neuron geometry and operator bundles plus an aggregated connectivity registry. Milestone 7 needs a first-class handoff contract for synapse-level data and inter-neuron coupling artifacts, but there is no canonical definition for where synapse-derived assets live, how downstream code discovers them, how coupling topology is encoded, or how sign, delay, aggregation, and morphology fallback decisions are documented. Without a versioned contract and a decisive design note, later simulator and UI work will bind itself to ad hoc filenames, undocumented semantics, and incompatible assumptions about what a \"coupling edge\" means.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/prompt.md:13:Define a first-class synapse and coupling contract for Milestone 7 and document the design choices behind it. Centralize asset naming and manifest metadata in library code, extend the processed manifest so downstream consumers can discover the local synapse registry plus any per-root or per-edge coupling artifacts without hardcoded paths, and add a markdown design note that compares the viable coupling-topology families before committing to the default. The design note should be decisive: choose the default among point-to-point, patch-to-patch, and distributed patch-cloud coupling, define the fallback hierarchy for surface, skeleton, and point-neuron representations, and state how sign, delay, missing geometry, and multi-synapse aggregation must be represented for later simulator code.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/prompt.md:16:- Synapse and coupling path construction is centralized in library code rather than being reimplemented inside scripts.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/prompt.md:17:- The processed manifest records an explicit synapse-contract or coupling-contract version plus discoverable pointers to the local synapse registry, anchor-map artifacts, coupling bundles, and the design-note version they conform to.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/prompt.md:18:- A dedicated markdown design note compares the supported coupling-topology families, chooses the default, names the supported fallback modes, and documents the invariants later milestones must preserve when consuming the coupling bundle.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/prompt.md:19:- `docs/pipeline_notes.md` is updated so the Milestone 7 contract sits alongside the existing geometry and operator contracts.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/prompt.md:24:- A focused unit test that builds fixture synapse or coupling metadata and asserts deterministic manifest serialization plus bundle discovery\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-001_Freeze_a_versioned_synapse_asset_contract_and_inter-neuron_coupling_design_note/prompt.md:27:This ticket should land first. Keep the contract boring and explicit: one place to build paths, one place to build metadata, and one in-repo design note that later tickets can cite instead of re-litigating the coupling model.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/prompt.md:1:Work ticket FW-M7-003: Map synapse locations onto surface patches and skeleton anchors with deterministic fallback metadata.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/prompt.md:4:Source: Milestone 7 roadmap 2026-03-21\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/prompt.md:10:Milestone 6 gives the repo per-neuron geometry, patch, and operator bundles, but nothing yet translates synapse locations into addresses on those state spaces. The roadmap explicitly calls for locating nearest patches or skeleton nodes and building fast lookup structures, yet the repo has no artifact or API that says where a postsynaptic landing sits on the receiving surface, where a presynaptic readout should be sampled, or how mapping quality and fallback decisions should be recorded when surface geometry is missing or unsuitable.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/prompt.md:13:Implement the synapse-anchor mapping layer that consumes the local synapse registry plus geometry bundles and emits deterministic lookup artifacts. Postsynaptic synapses should map to receiving-surface anchors using the default resolution chosen in `FW-M7-001`, while presynaptic sites should map to the corresponding readout anchors on the source neuron. The implementation must support the documented fallback hierarchy for surface, skeleton, and point-neuron representations, serialize mapping distances and residuals, and provide fast query helpers for common access patterns such as inbound synapses to a root, outbound synapses from a root, and all mapped synapses for one edge.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/prompt.md:16:- A first-class mapping artifact or sidecar is written for the mapped roots or edges and is discoverable from the manifest or coupling contract.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/prompt.md:17:- Each mapped synapse records presynaptic and postsynaptic anchor information, chosen anchor type and resolution, mapping quality metrics, and any fallback or blocked-prerequisite reason.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/prompt.md:18:- Library helpers support efficient edge-level and root-level lookups without requiring downstream simulator code to scan the entire raw synapse table.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/prompt.md:24:- A fixture-driven test that maps synthetic synapses onto a small mesh and optional skeleton and asserts anchor assignments, lookup outputs, and fallback metadata\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/prompt.md:27:Assume `FW-M7-001` and `FW-M7-002` have landed. Keep the raw nearest-neighbor mechanics inspectable and deterministic; later physics work will only be credible if the localization layer is easy to audit.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/last_message.md:1:Implemented FW-M7-003 in [synapse_mapping.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/src/flywire_wave/synapse_mapping.py#L229): the repo now materializes deterministic per-root incoming/outgoing anchor maps, per-edge coupling bundles, and root-local coupling indexes from the local synapse registry. Surface roots map to coarse patch anchors, skeleton fallback maps to nearest SWC nodes, point fallback maps to deterministic lumped anchors, and each synapse side records query provenance, anchor type/resolution, distances, residuals, mapping status, quality status, and fallback or blocked reasons. Lookup helpers now cover inbound-root, outbound-root, and per-edge access without scanning the raw synapse table. [03_build_wave_assets.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/scripts/03_build_wave_assets.py#L276) now builds those artifacts during the normal asset pass and writes realized `coupling_bundle` metadata into the manifest instead of leaving placeholders.\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/last_message.md:3:Coverage was added in [test_synapse_mapping.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/tests/test_synapse_mapping.py#L34) for deterministic surface mapping plus skeleton, point, and blocked-coordinate cases, and the path-based integration assertions were updated in [test_config_paths.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/tests/test_config_paths.py#L82). I also documented the shipped status and fallback semantics in [pipeline_notes.md](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/docs/pipeline_notes.md) and [coupling_bundle_design.md](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/docs/coupling_bundle_design.md).\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T222203Z/FW-M7-003_Map_synapse_locations_onto_surface_patches_and_skeleton_anchors_with_deterministic_fallback_metadata/last_message.md:5:Verified with `.venv/bin/python -m unittest tests.test_synapse_mapping -v` and `make test` (53 tests passed).\nagent_tickets/runs/20260321T185349Z/FW-M6-001_Freeze_a_versioned_operator_bundle_contract_and_discretization_design_note/stdout.jsonl:6:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_1\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin